@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{soudesu}}}} can be used to reply to a noun sentence in the affirmative.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{soreha@KJ{{book}}desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{hai,@EM{{soudesu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is this a book?      
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yes it is.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
To answer the same question in the negative, use @HI{{@EM{{sou jaarimasenn}}}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{soreha@KJ{{hon}}desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{iie,@EM{{soujaarimasenn}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is this a book?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No it isn't.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

An equivalent negative response would be to use @KJ{{difference}}@HI{{imasu}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{soreha@KJ{{hon}}desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{iie,@KJ{{chiga}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is this a book?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No, you are mistaken.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

